    "body": "### Problem\n\nLiteral `\\t` in floating window title and footer results in bad rendering.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create the following 'init.lua':\n\n    ```lua\n    _G.show_floatwin = function()\n      local config = { relative = 'editor', row = 2, col = 2, height = 2, width = 10 }\n      config.border = 'single'\n      config.title = 'a\\tb\\t\\tc'\n      config.footer = 'A\\tB\\t\\tC'\n      vim.api.nvim_open_win(vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, true), false, config)\n    end\n    ```\n\n2. `nvim --clean -u init.lua`\n3. `:lua show_floatwin()`. It will show the floating window, but both title and footer are out of place due to `\\t` being rendered as 'tabstop' spaces. This happens both right after start (with splash screen visible) and after doing some text editing to make sure that redraw rules are \"as usual\". Here is how the latter case looks:\n\n<img width=\"2880\" height=\"1734\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a1903111-da4c-4f74-ab38-dd0b96569ea4\" />\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nProbably that literal `\\t` is shown in the same way as in other special UI places. Like in 'statusline' it is shown as `^I`.\n\nAnother approach is to expand the title respecting 'tabstop', but then truncate it as if it has literal `tabstop` number of spaces.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev-606+g3600d1c13c\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, doesn't have this functionality\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nEndeavourOS Linux x86_64, 7.0.9-arch2-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.3.1-arch2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nAppimage",
